<p><b>Samson Abramsky</b> <a href="/wiki/Royal_Society" title="Royal Society">FRS</a> (born 12 March 1953), <a href="/wiki/Royal_Society_of_Edinburgh" title="Royal Society of Edinburgh">FRSE</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Computer_science" title="Computer science">computer scientist</a> who holds the <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Strachey" title="Christopher Strachey">Christopher Strachey</a> Professorship at the <a href="/wiki/Department_of_Computer_Science,_University_of_Oxford" title="Department of Computer Science, University of Oxford">Department of Computer Science (formerly the Computing Laboratory), University of Oxford</a>. He has made contributions to the areas of <a href="/wiki/Domain_theory" title="Domain theory">domain theory</a>, the lazy <a href="/wiki/Lambda_calculus" title="Lambda calculus">lambda calculus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Strictness_analysis" title="Strictness analysis">strictness analysis</a>, <a href="/wiki/Concurrency_theory" title="Concurrency theory" class="mw-redirect">concurrency theory</a>, interaction categories, <a href="/wiki/Geometry_of_interaction" title="Geometry of interaction">geometry of interaction</a>, <a href="/wiki/Game_semantics" title="Game semantics">game semantics</a> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=Quantum_computer_science&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Quantum computer science (page does not exist)">quantum computer science</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-googlescholar_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-googlescholar-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-scopus_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-scopus-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-linkedin_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-linkedin-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-dblp_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dblp-9"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-acm_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-acm-11"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-microsoft_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-microsoft-12"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup> </p>
